{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778536814,"nonce":"uQYd8i7krYpgQWNzhKMwmjR0pfA=","title":"Add power-law schedule option to make_late_discount_from_epoch","message":"The rlrmp helper `make_late_discount_from_epoch` (`src/rlrmp/loss.py:277-303`) currently supports `smooth=\"cosine\"` and `smooth=\"linear\"` ramp shapes. To support faithful C\u0026S 2019 `(t/N)^6` back-loading in upcoming experiments, add a `smooth=\"power_law\"` option with a `power` parameter that returns `(t/T)^power` directly (not a cosine approximation).\n\n## Implementation\n\nAdd branch in `make_late_discount_from_epoch`:\n```\nif smooth == \"power_law\":\n    weight = (t / T) ** power  # match C\u0026S 2019 Eq. 15 normalization\n```\n\nExpose via:\n- New CLI flags in `train_minimax.py`: `--effector-pos-late-smooth {cosine,linear,power_law}` and `--effector-pos-late-power \u003cfloat\u003e`.\n- New `nn_hidden_derivative_pre_go` or related epoch-masked variants if needed for completeness.\n- Apply analogously to any other discount/ramp helpers that should support power-law.\n\n## Why\n\nCosine ramp is qualitatively similar to `(t/N)^6` but not the same shape. For comparison against C\u0026S 2019 analytical Riccati results (which use exactly `(t/N)^6`), we need the faithful schedule.\n\n## Used by\n\n- Lit-replication 6-cell matrix (next issue) for cells 2, 3, 5, 6 which use `(t/N)^6` shape variants.\n\n## References\n\n- C\u0026S 2019 Eq. 15: `α₁(t/N)^6 · x^T Q x` in the cost function (cs2019.pdf, page 8138).\n- Existing schedule code: `src/rlrmp/loss.py:277-303`.","files":null}]}